</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS BAKER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Houston guard Vernon Maxwell guarantees that the Rockets will beat the Phoenix 
Suns in the seventh game of the NBA Western Conference semifinals today at the 
Summit. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're definitely going to win," Maxwell said shortly after being ejected in 
the fourth quarter of Thursday night's 103-89 loss at Phoenix."We're going to 
get ready to play whoever wins the game in Utah (today between the Jazz and the 
Denver Nuggets in the other Western Conference semifinal)." 
</P>
<P>
 Rocket center Hakeem Olajuwon isn't as confident that Houston will advance to 
the Western Conference finals for the third time in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nobody can guarantee the future," Olajuwon said. "But we're in a very good 
position. We have to be smart, play with confidence and take care of business." 
</P>
<P>
 Maxwell will need to shoot better than he did Thursday for the Rockets to make 
good on his prediction. He had 34 points in Game 3, his best playoff game ever, 
but made only two of 10 shots and scored six points in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
 Guard Kenny Smith didn't shoot much better, missing eight of 11 shots and 
scoring eight points. 
</P>
<P>
 Phoenix guard Kevin Johnson, who overcame a bad Game 5 by getting 28 points 
and 13 assists in Game 6, expects the Suns to advance. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're very confident. We've been in this situation many times," Johnson said. 
"We're looking forward to it. We're going to try to rediscover what we're made 
of." 
