<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRIAL SEEMS LIKELY FOR VAN BUREN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KENNEDY COSGROVE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Neither side changed its position Friday when Ventura County prosecutors and 
the attorney for Leodes Van Buren met to discuss the felony weapons charge 
faced by the All-State football player from Newbury Park High. 
</P>
<P>
 Both sides expect the case to go to trial in Superior Court, probably next 
month.A preliminary hearing is scheduled for Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Van Buren, 18, was arrested April 8 on suspicion of firing a single shot from 
a handgun through the back door of his girlfriend's home in Newbury Park. 
</P>
<P>
 Van Buren contends that a companion actually pulled the trigger. 
</P>
<P>
 The status of Van Buren's football scholarship at Colorado is uncertain 
pending the outcome of the case. 
</P>
<P>
 The 6-foot-1, 190-pound wide receiver led Newbury Park to the Southern Section 
Division III championship last fall. He is the state's all-time leader in 
receptions and receiving yardage. KENNEDY COSGROVE 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA052194-0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 043844 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
May 21, 1994, Saturday, Valley Edition 
</P>
