</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HADLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Four months after the devastating Northridge earthquake, the Moorpark City 
Council is requesting that the Federal Emergency Management Agency pay for the 
demolition of an 80-year-old market knocked off its foundation during the 
temblor. 
</P>
<P>
 The city is requesting that FEMA pay $29,000 as the cost of demolishing the 
Mayflower Market on High Street and a wall at the Metrolink station. 
</P>
<P>
 Rifaat Hijaz, owner of the 20-year-old family business, said he is eager to 
have the building razed. 
</P>
<P>
 "The sooner they take it down the better," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Hijaz has operated the market out of a nearby storage shed. His family is 
eager to rebuild, but is still waiting on a $300,000 low-interest disaster loan 
from the U.S. Small Business Administration. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't know why it's taking so long, I wish I knew," he said.  
</P>
<P>
 "At least the city has been helpful." SCOTT HADLY 
