<HEADLINE>
<P>
L.A. PRODUCE SUPPLIER MOVING TO LOS ALAMITOS; FOODSTUFFS: FRIEDA'S INC., WHICH 
POPULARIZED THE KIWI FRUIT, PACKING UP HEADQUARTERS AND 115 EMPLOYEES TO 
CORPORATE CENTER SITE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WOODYARD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Frieda's Inc., a specialty produce supplier best known for popularizing kiwi 
fruit in the United States, is moving its headquarters and 115 employees here 
from Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 The company, the seventh-largest women-owned business in Los Angeles, has 
leased an 81,000-square-foot office and warehouse in Los Alamitos Corporate 
Center on Cerritos Avenue near Lexington Drive. 
</P>
<P>
 The move, to be completed by July 1, ends a three-year search for a new and 
larger base of operations. Nearly all of the employees are expected to make the 
20-mile relocation. 
</P>
<P>
 Frieda's, which distributes more than 400 exotic fruits, vegetables and other 
foods, has annual sales of more than $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
 The company's new headquarters building was previously occupied by PCH 
Clothing Co., which moved to Huntington Beach, said Frieda's President Karen 
Caplan. 
</P>
<P>
 "The building found us," Caplan said, explaining that the company had been 
looking for sites near its downtown Los Angeles location to stay close to 
produce dealers. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Los Alamitos building was so perfectly suited, she said, that the 
distance became less important. 
</P>
<P>
 The company was founded in 1962 by Karen Caplan's mother, Frieda Caplan, who 
began selling California brown mushrooms from a stall in the old 7th Street 
wholesale market in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Later that year, Frieda Caplan came across a hairy brown fruit from New 
Zealand called the Chinese gooseberry. She renamed it kiwi and began promoting 
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
